They dont use alcohol to clean the area (at least I'm pretty sure) they dont really have any tubes except for inthabation (helps you breathe) and they dont use have lasers in the room if it isnt necessary. I've expressed my opinion on Elisa Lam's death in a video about the elevator footage and I'd like to do the same here. I'm 90% sure she was murdered by a serial killer.   The Cecil hotel has a history of serial killers residing there during their activity. Elisa's death seems to be a case of life imitating art. The circumstances in which her body was found are the exact same as those in the 2005 movie Dark Water and other details are similar as well; malfunctioning elevator  the hotel's name being very similar to that of a girl in the movie (Cecilia). Coincidence? I don't believe so? Planned? Most likely. Let me explain.  There are serial killers that decide to kill a person in the same way they see it portrayed in a book or a movie. Elisa was most likely scared she was being followed as she entered the elevator and her fears must have gotten out of control due to her bipolar disorder  which would explain her strange behaviour. I also believe she was already dead when thrown into the water tank and did not die there from drowning.   I suspect her cause of death was a prescription medication overdose (she was taking medication for bipolar disorder and depression). She might have taken them herself in hopes to calm down when she realised she was being followed  or maybe the killer forced her to take a large amount so as not to leave any external signs on her body. I also believe she was anally raped and the overdose gave its effect by the time she was getting raped or after.   As to why the autopsy didn't reveal any signs of intoxication from medication  it could have been due to the fact that she was found two weeks after her death and her body was decomposing in water  which might have washed away important evidence.   Moreover  death from overdose is actually hard to determine  especially in people who get an overdose of their long-time medication  because their body builds a resistance that might cover the effects of overdose after some time. This article explains everything very well:  http://content.time.com/time/health/article/0 8599 1996831 00.html  I might be very wrong of course  this is just my theory. But overall  it is my belief that she was  most certainly  murdered.

I'm so happy that Shane's helping Bunny  but it also breaks my heart hearing her talk down about herself. I've been watching Bunny since around 2012 after stumbling across her channel while looking for paranormal stuff  and I loved her immediately. I loved her stories  her personality  her style. I never saw another Youtuber that I really felt like I could relate to until her. I stuck with her for a long time even as she changed things up and became more loud and high-energy. I loved her the whole time  but eventually my interest kinda died out for awhile. I never unsubbed  but I just felt like her videos were getting really repetitive and she seems kinda empty compared to who she used to be. My favorite videos of hers are the ones where she's just being honest and opening up about her opinions and feelings. I love hearing her vent/rant  her channel's always felt like chilling with a friend even though I've never met her. She doesn't have to act cheerful and excited and play with toys all the time to get my attention  I've just always looked up to her and admired her for who she is as a person  whether she's just talking or throwing around a giant ball in her backyard. I just want her to do what she wants to do  not necessarily that she has to show us everything  but that she can be more open with her viewers and not be happy 24/7 because no person is. I totally relate with what she's saying though-- how she feels the need to "die and start over" when things get too bad  but she can't remember how to and feels stuck. I'm in that same boat right now  that's why I love how relatable she can be. I'm just glad my two favorite Youtubers are finally interacting and Shane's helping her get back into the swing of things. It's been such a bummer watching her fall into this funk. Thank you  Shane. <3
